e any convex function.
 Therefore, the last results seem to suggest that general convex problems
 are as easy as general linear systems for now.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Understanding the bounds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the runtimes should have the correct 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

units
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 For instance, if the unit of the function value is 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 (Joule) and the unit of the space is 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, then the units of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $Jm^{-1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Therefore, the number of iterations of gradient descent 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{GR}{\epsilon}$
\end_inset

 is unitless.
 In the table, we ignored some entries inside the 
\begin_inset Formula $\log$
\end_inset

 which leads to an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

incorrect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 unit.
 However, when everything is written correctly, the number of iterations
 must be unitless.
 Furthermore, we can view 
\begin_inset Formula $GR$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $LR^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{G^{2}}{\mu}$
\end_inset

 all as upper bounds of the initial error 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x^{(0)})-f^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, we know that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x^{(0)})-f^{*}\leq\left\langle \nabla f(x^{(0)}),x^{(0)}-x^{*}\right\rangle \leq GR
\]

\end_inset

and that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x^{(0)})-f^{*}\leq\left\langle \nabla f(x^{*}),x^{(0)}-x^{*}\right\rangle +\frac{L}{2}\|x^{(0)}-x^{*}\|^{2}\leq LR^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore, the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{GR}{k}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{G^{2}}{\mu k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{LR^{2}}{k}$
\end_inset

 are all just measuring how much we need to decrease multiplicatively from
 the initial error.
 With this view, we can think the number of iteration required for Lipschitz
 convex functions, strongly convex functions and smooth functions are exactly
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\epsilon_{\mathrm{relative}}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\epsilon_{\mathrm{relative}}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\sqrt{\epsilon_{\mathrm{relative}}}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $L/\mu$
\end_inset

 can be dimension dependent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $L/\mu$
\end_inset

 heavily depends on the application.
 For some easy problems, it can be as small as 
\begin_inset Formula $O(1)$
\end_inset

.
 However, it can be very large for many natural problems.
 Here we give a few examples of natural convex functions with huge 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{L}{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 One very simple example is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\frac{1}{2}x_{1}^{2}+\frac{1}{2}\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}(x_{k}-x_{k+1})^{2}+\frac{1}{2}x_{n}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

This problem appears everywhere from physical systems, graph problems, signal
 denoising to statistics.
 For this problem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\Theta(1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\Theta(\frac{1}{n^{2}})$
\end_inset

.
 This example shows that you can have large 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{L}{\mu}$
\end_inset

 even with small description coefficients in the problem.
 Here is another example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\norm{Ax-b}_{2}^{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a random 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix with independent Gaussian entries.
 For this problem, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\Theta(n)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\Theta(\frac{1}{n})$
\end_inset

 with high probability.
 For an extreme example, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|$
\end_inset

 has both 
\begin_inset Formula $L=+\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Accuracy of analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For gradient descent and accelerated gradient descent, the convergence rate
 is asymptotically accurate if we take 
\begin_inset Formula $L\sim\lambda_{\max}(\nabla^{2}f(x^{*}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\sim\lambda_{\min}(\nabla^{2}f(x^{*}))$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is because any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 function locally looks like a quadratic around its minimum.
 We take gradient descent as an example.
 Note that gradient descent is invariant under any rotation and translation
 transformation.
 Therefore, we can assume 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=0$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}f(x^{*})$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix with diagonals 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2},\cdots,\lambda_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is close to the optimal 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}=0$
\end_inset

, gradient descent 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\new}=x-h\nabla f(x)$
\end_inset

 is similar to a coordinate-wise iteration 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}^{\new}=(1-h\lambda_{i})x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This gives a precise description of the convergence rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For more complicated algorithms, the theory of convergence rate and cost
 per iteration sometimes gives a bad estimate of the reality.
 For example, the interior point method often takes 
\begin_inset Formula $O(\log n)$
\end_inset

 iterations to converge despite its 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}$
\end_inset

 bound on convergence rate; simplex method is often the best of choice for
 solving linear programs despite its exponential complexity bound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cost per iterations sometimes can be misleading also.
 Each iteration of interior point methods takes 
\begin_inset Formula $\nnz(A)+\mathrm{rank}(A)^{2}$
\end_inset

 in theory while it takes nearly linear time in practice for sparse matrices
 due to the effectiveness of Cholesky decomposition.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{th}$
\end_inset

 iteration of cutting plane methods often takes 
\begin_inset Formula $nk+k^{O(1)}$
\end_inset

 if implemented correctly despite its super-linear bound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, the error of floating point computation gradually starts to have
 an effect when the target accuracy 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 is small.
\end_layout

